how do you make homemade sweet pickles i tried some homemade sweet pickles last summer that somebody made my mother and they were delicious when i tried to get the recipe of course she said to add a pinch of this and a bit of that i need a precise recipe if possible thanks kirby cucumbers or regular cucumbers cup kosher salt cup water cup rice vinegar cup sugar tablespoon coriander seed tablespoon mustard seed tablespoon whole allspice berries cinnamon stick cloves bay leaf wash and dry the cucumbers using a sharp knife or a mandolin slice the cucumbers thinly and place in a colander sprinkle with salt and toss to coat place the colander over a bowl and allow it to sit covered for about hour rinse off the salt and dry the cucumber slices well place them into a sterilized quart jar in a small saucepan add the remaining ingredients stir to dissolve sugar and bring to a boil remove from heat and allow it to cool pour the brine over the cucumbers in jar cover and refrigerate at least hours preferably overnight will keep refrigerated for about weeks tips on sterilizing jars properly handled sterilized equipment will keep canned foods in good condition for years sterilizing jars is the first step of preserving foods sterilizing tips jars should be made from glass and free of any chips or cracks preserving or canning jars are topped with a glass plastic or metal lid which has a rubber seal two piece lids are best for canning as they vacuum seal when processed to sterilize jars before filling with jams pickles or preserves wash jars and lids with hot soapy water rinse well and arrange jars and lids open sides up without touching on a tray leave in a preheated degree f oven for minutes or boil the jars and lids in a large saucepan covered with water for minutes use tongs when handling the hot sterilized jars to move them from either boiling water or the oven be sure the tongs are sterilized too by dipping the ends in boiling water for a few minutes as a rule hot preserves go into hot jars and cold preserves go into cold jars all items used in the process of making jams jellies and preserves must be clean this includes any towels used and especially your hands after the jars are sterilized you can preserve the food it is important to follow any canning and processing instructions included in the recipe and refer to usda guidelines about the sterilization of canned products Cuisine of the Philippines Barbecue Vinegar Mayonnaise Cantonese cuisine Agar plate Casting Haggis Cookware and bakeware Cuisine of Brazil Bacon Chili con carne Hamster Pickled cucumber Ham Menstrual cup Textile manufacturing Bagel Food Yoghurt Soap Rice pudding Rum Dairy Pottery Ice cream Kosher foods Breakfast Korean cuisine Sandwich Sugar beet Potato chips German cuisine Sterilization (microbiology) Cheese Hydrochloric acid Curry Wine making Fishing Milk Bong Manicure Russian cuisine Glass Cajun cuisine Wok Cuisine of Malaysia Recipe Sugar Knife Bengali cuisine Sento Ramen Kitchen Peruvian cuisine Soy milk Dishwasher Cooking weights and measures Beer Welding Pancake Soul food Cincinnati chili Fujian tea ceremony Turkish coffee Roast beef Dishwashing Tattoo Cuisine of Singapore Apple pie Soldering Sea-Monkey Basil Soup Martini cocktail First aid Kashrut 